It sounds like you’ve built a sleek, minimal, and highly customized stack. Moving from Bash to Zsh or Fish is a classic "quality of life" crossroads. Since you’re already using Kanata for keyboard remapping and Hyprland for your WM, you clearly value efficiency and "the right feel."

Here is the breakdown of how Zsh and Fish handle the trade-offs between robustness, configuration, and that elusive perfect Vi mode.

1. Zsh (The Power-User's Standard)
Zsh is effectively "Bash Plus." It is POSIX-compliant enough that most of your Bash scripts will run fine, but it adds deep customizability.

Pros
Robustness: It is the industry standard (default on macOS and Kali). It won't break your existing workflow.

The Best Vi Mode: With the zsh-vi-mode plugin, Zsh offers the most robust Vi emulation in any shell, including visual mode and surround support.

Completion System: Its complist module is legendary. You can tab-complete through menus with arrow keys.

Cons
Configuration Debt: To get the "modern" feel (syntax highlighting, autosuggestions), you have to install several plugins. This can lead to the "configuration hassle" you're trying to avoid.

Boilerplate: Without a framework like Oh My Zsh (which can be bloated) or Antidote, setting it up from scratch takes time.

2. Fish (The Friendly Interactive Shell)
Fish takes a "batteries-included" approach. It discards POSIX compliance to provide a better user experience out of the box.

Pros
Zero-Config Shine: Syntax highlighting, autosuggestions (based on history), and web-based configuration work instantly without editing a single file.

Native Vi Mode: Fish has a very solid built-in Vi mode. You just add fish_vi_key_bindings to your config, and it even changes the cursor shape natively to reflect the mode.

Scripting Clarity: The syntax is much cleaner than Bash. No more confusing if [ $X -eq 0 ] syntax; it’s just if test $X = 0.

Cons
Not POSIX Compliant: This is the big one. You cannot "source" a Bash script in Fish. If you find a cool tool online that says export PATH=$PATH:/opt/bin, that command will fail in Fish (it uses set -gx PATH ...).

Robustness vs. Compatibility: While the shell itself is rock solid, the friction comes when you have to "translate" standard Linux snippets into Fish-speak.

