Gemini said
You are 100% correct, and your intuition hits on the "secret" of why many people successfully use Fish despite its reputation.

The "Shebang" Reality
When you run a script like ./script.sh or bash script.sh, your interactive shell (Fish/Zsh) doesn't execute the code itself. It looks at the Shebang (#!/bin/bash) or the command you typed (bash) and hands the job over to the Bash binary.

Because of this, 99% of scripts you download or write will work perfectly fine regardless of your shell.

Where the "Incompatibility" Actually Bites You
The "Hassle" isn't about running scripts; it’s about environment integration. Here are the three places where Fish will actually annoy you:

1. The "Sourcing" Problem
Many tools (like nvm, conda, fzf, or even some Arch-specific SDKs) ask you to add a line like this to your config:
source /usr/share/doc/pkg/setup.sh

In Zsh: This works instantly.

In Fish: This will fail because setup.sh is written in Bash. You then have to:

Find a Fish-specific version of the tool (e.g., nvm.fish).

Use a "wrapper" like plugin-foreign-env to bridge the gap.

2. Variable Exporting
If you find a tutorial that says "just run this to fix your Hyprland scaling":
export GDK_BACKEND=wayland

In Zsh: You paste it, it works.

In Fish: You get a syntax error. You have to type set -gx GDK_BACKEND wayland.

3. Subshells and Strings
Fish doesn't use the backtick ` for command substitution, and it handles quotes differently.

Bash/Zsh: kill -9 $(pgrep ghostty)

Fish: kill -9 (pgrep ghostty) (No dollar sign for commands).

The "Robustness" Trade-off
If you want "Thorough and Robust," here is how the two philosophies clash:

Zsh is Robust through Compatibility: It is the "correct" way to do things in the Linux ecosystem. It follows the rules that have existed since the 70s. If a tool breaks, it's the tool's fault, not Zsh's.

Fish is Robust through Simplicity: It is robust because it doesn't have 40 years of legacy "weirdness." It has a clear, modern syntax. It’s robust because it's hard to accidentally write a "bad" Fish script.

The Verdict for an Arch/Hyprland User
Since you are on Arch, you likely use the AUR. Some AUR packages rely on setting environment variables via /etc/profile or similar scripts.

If you hate translating syntax: Choose Zsh. It’s the "path of least resistance" for a power user who wants everything to "just work" with the rest of the Linux world.

If you don't mind the "Fish Tax": (the 30 seconds it takes to google the Fish equivalent of a Bash command), choose Fish. The interactive experience is genuinely more enjoyable.

One last tip: Since you use Ghostty, it actually handles some of the environment variable handoffs very gracefully. If you set your variables in your .zshenv or your Fish config properly, your Hyprland environment won't even notice the difference.

