Yes, you can absolutely just run bash script.sh. In fact, since almost every script starts with #!/bin/bash, your shell automatically hands it off to Bash anyway.

The "Foreign Environment" problem is actually much narrower: it's when a Bash script needs to change your current shell's settings (like adding a tool to your $PATH or setting a secret $API_KEY).

In Fish, you handle this using a tiny tool called Bass.

1. The Solution: Bass
Bass allows you to run a Bash command and "absorb" its environment changes back into Fish.

Install it (using the Fisher plugin manager):

Code snippet
fisher install edc/bass
Use it for sourcing:
If a tool (like nvm or a custom script) tells you to do source setup.sh, you just type:

Code snippet
bass source setup.sh
Bass runs the script in Bash, sees what variables changed, and sets them in your Fish session for you.

2. The "Robust" Pro-Tip: Don't Change Your Login Shell
Since you’re on Arch and use a complex setup (Hyprland, Kanata), changing your system login shell (chsh) to Fish can sometimes break system-level scripts that expect a POSIX shell.

The robust way to do this is to keep Bash as your system shell but tell your terminal (Ghostty) to start Fish by default.

In your ghostty config:

Plaintext
command = /usr/bin/fish
This gives you the best of both worlds:

System Stability: Your OS sees you as a Bash user (no broken scripts).

Interactive Joy: Every time you open Ghostty, you’re in Fish with Starship and Vi mode.

3. Making Vi Mode "Thorough" in Fish
To stop the "hassle" of Vi mode not working, put this in your ~/.config/fish/config.fish:

Code snippet
if status is-interactive
    # Start Vi mode
    fish_vi_key_bindings
    
    # Custom bind: 'jk' to escape (if that's your Neovim habit)
    bind -M insert -m default jk backward-char force-repaint
    
    # Cursor shapes (to match Neovim)
    set fish_cursor_default block
    set fish_cursor_insert line
    set fish_cursor_replace_one underscore
end
